All of this is far more than we ever thought we'd accomplish when we first decided that perhaps what we wanted to do was start our own company.
And it's a great base for FA to build on as it goes forward to do more great work, without me (sniff).

A final project I'd like to highlight is the ASAE Foundation's ForesightWorks project. FA has been the proud partner and contractor for ASAE Foundation, helping the build a storehouse of foresight resources for their members that includes briefs, change drivers and workshops.

You can read that here: 
https://t.co/BK2VnmA97j

Next, we undertook a year-long study for the Rockefeller Foundation on the Futures of Work. I am proud of this, as a lot of people were focusing on impact on white collar/knowledge work, we delved into the impact on all social/economic levels.

Our next big-both in content and in scope-project was Food 2040, a look at the future of food & agriculture in East Asia, which launched us into the ag and commodities sector, where we have continued to work. https://t.co/fFQQ7NwkmD
It was not something that garnered any outside recognition, but it was proof of concept for FA and demonstrated we could run our own consulting firm.
Right out of the gate we landed a project with a food and beverage company about the future of food, nutrition, and wellness, helping the client identify early signals of change in those areas.

We created FA at the height (depths?) of the recession of 2008-09, joking we were either the worst or best futurists for starting a consulting company at a time when everyone was shedding contractors. 13 yrs later, I think we proved to be ok futurists.

Some personal news: After 13 very rewarding years, Friday was my last day with Foresight Alliance. I just wanted to take a moment to highlight some projects we did over the years demonstrate what Foresight Alliance can do.

So there you have it online advertising world, one person's anecdotal experience!
Interestingly too, very few I've talked to (and again, I fully realize this is anecdotal) have had a hyper-relevant ad come up and then said, "Oh, right, I needed that. <click>"

And yes, we all realize that it is the ads that make things free ("free") on the Internet, but no one I've talked to over the years has been like, "Yeah, ads suck, but these relevant ones make it less sucky." They all stop at "ads suck."

And no one pushes back on this assumption. Meanwhile, in my anecdotal conversations over the years the talk has been just ads vs. no ads. No one cares if the ads are super relevant, they are still annoyed becasue there are ads.

Am I a perfect driver? No, nor should I have to be to express frustration about basic pedestrian safety issues. But while I am not perfect, I certainly do not honk at peds in the crosswalk, and then almost kill them by illegally pulling out and around the car in front of me.

In the past 10 years my "what if you could have one super power wish" has become, the power to cause bad drivers to have a non-injurious crash that leaves them with tens of thousands of dollars in repairs, fines, and restitution.
This is not even car/bike interaction. This is a person (me!) crossing in a crosswalk at a stop sign, and almost being hit by someone too impatient to wait 20 seconds for me to cross.
I said nothing--NOTHING-- to him, just glared as I continued to cross. He then rolled down his window and told me to 'fuck off.' For crossing the street.

Am I salty about this? Sure. But as I was in a cross-walk today in front of a service truck, driver behind truck started honking for it to go, not being able to see I was there. Driver then decided to pull around truck and then stopped (thankfully) when he saw me.
To sum up, remember kids, it's not murder if you use a vehicle.

To say, "There is always other work and always other jobs" is to console someone about the clearcutting of a popular grove of trees in their neighborhood by saying, "There have always been trees and there are other forests."

Is dehumanizing and demoralizing. It sets people on to a path they don't want to be on and can't escape from because very little of the economic gain generated from increased productivity is set aside to support the job dispossessed.

The idea that "there is always work" eliminates the idea that one should--CAN!--enjoy their job, and not just do work because it is the default human condition. Automation forcing people to take jobs they don't want because their old job is gone & there is no $$ for retraining ..

And this piece highlights other areas for the displaced waitstaff to apply: healthcare, warehouse work, etc, but why would someone who LIKES being a waiter go to work in healthcare? or at at warehouse?

In any of these cases, where are the resources to help them find new work when their old jobs are automated in a blaze of 'productivity' glory that is heralded as a benefit to all? Where is the support for the waiter who could only get that job?

The jobs in this article are restaurant jobs. Now, some people working these jobs undoubtedly want better jobs. But some whose jobs will be eliminated LIKE being waitstaff, and there are some whose circumstances are such this is the only work they can find.

And then the next statement is always, "Well this allows them to get better jobs elsewhere" as if a worker in a job has never thought about getting a better job elsewhere. But how? It would be nice if society provided tools to do this beyond, "Well we have eliminated your job."

It's the move from the specific to the general, and in this case from today to the past. No one worried about losing their jobs to automation is saying that they also want to live in 1700s England. What they are saying is, "I don't want to be replaced by automation."
